<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <link href="styles.css" rel="stylesheet">
</head>
<body>
<div class="canvas-app" >
<div style="border:1px solid #666666; padding:15px;"> 
    <img src="rbclogo.jpg"/>
    <p>Hello, <%= context.user.firstName %>. This is a web app written in Node.js embedded in your Salesforce page (It could also be written in any other language).</p>
    <p> <b> It is aware of its environment.</b> For example, here are a few things it knows:</p>
    <table>
        <tr><td>User:</td><td><%= context.user.fullName %></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Object:</td><td><%= context.environment.record.attributes.type %></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Id:</td><td><%= context.environment.record.Id %></td></tr>
         <tr><td>Contact First Name:</td><td><%= context.environment.record.attributes.Name %></td></tr>
           <tr><td>Contact Last Name:</td><td><%= context.environment.record.Name %></td></tr>
    </table>
    <p>It can also access more data in Salesforce using the REST APIs. With context and APIs, 
    <b> Canvas makes it easy to integrate applications written in any language inside your Salesforce pages. </b> </p>
    <p> In the following screen, an API call from an external app shows balances for the contact  in context - the contact whose record page
 page we are in.</p>
    <img src="balances.jpg"/>
  </div>
</div>
</body>
